---
title: "Predictive Statistical Mechanics"
year: 1986
abstract: >
  Jaynes provides a broad survey of Predictive Statistical Mechanics, a line of
  thought that sees statistical mechanics not as a physical theory, but as a
  form of statistical inference. He explains the historical development of this
  viewpoint, its relationship to the foundational problems of quantum theory
  (such as EPR and measurement), and its impressive practical successes in fields
  like spectrum analysis and image reconstruction. The work emphasizes the role
  of the Principle of Maximum Entropy (PME) in constructing unbiased prior
  probability assignments from incomplete information, and proposes that Bohr's
  and Einstein's views of quantum theory may eventually be unified through this
  generalized logic of scientific inference.
author: ["E.T. Jaynes"]
categories: ["Quantum Mechanics & Advanced Physics"]
tags: ["predictive statistical mechanics", "information theory", "Maximum Entropy", "Bayesian inference", "quantum theory", "spectrum analysis", "image reconstruction", "irreversible processes"]
---
