   607	## GENERALIZED INVERSE PROBLEM
   608	If the likelihood function L(M) = p(D|MI) does not peak sharply at any
   609	definite value of M but has a very broad maximum, the frequentist
   610	maximum likelihood principle becomes unstable, a small change in the
   611	data leading to a large change in the estimate, which common sense
   612	rejects as unreasonable. This makes the determination of the prior
   613	probabilities a more exacting task; the prior information is no longer
   614	overwhelmed by the data, and so it must be considered more carefully
   615	than Laplace needed to.
